Risk Management Analysis
Scenario 1: Hedging Market Risk
Lock in today’s futures price to protect against expected price increases.
•	Eliminates upside price risk
•	Provides cost certainty
Buy call options on coffee futures.
•	Protects against price increases
•	Preserves benefit if prices fall
•	Downside limited to option premium
Buy a call and sell a put to reduce premium cost.
•	Caps upside exposure
•	Reduces hedge cost
•	Balanced risk profile
Scenario 2: Credit Risk with a New Supplier
Use a bank-issued letter of credit.
•	Transfers default risk to the bank
•	Common in international trade
•	Reduces counterparty risk
Require Collateral or Advance Guarantees
•	Partial prepayment structure
•	Performance bonds
•	Trade credit insurance
Limit Exposure and Stagger Contracts
•	Start with smaller contract size
•	Use short-duration agreements
•	Gradually increase exposure if reliability proven
Scenario 3: Operational Risk in Trade Execution
Automation of Trade Capture
•	Implement electronic trading systems
•	Straight-through processing (STP)
•	Reduce manual input
Segregation of Duties
•	Separate trade execution
•	Trade confirmation
•	Settlement functions
Prevents fraud and internal errors.
Real-Time Reconciliation and Controls
•	Automated reconciliation systems
•	Exception reporting
•	Daily P&L verification
Staff Training and Control Reviews
•	Regular compliance checks
•	Operational audits
•	Scenario-based testing
